{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ec85ddc8-7df2-4e90-a326-bef477d54620","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads **at their current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by a new SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK moved forward → workloads need to catch up → `dotnet workload update`.\n\nIf issues persist after updating, you can also try:\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet workload repair   # only if update alone didn't help\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8e0e2717-f154-4876-838e-f62d63762765","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":248,"requestId":"DBC5:127F79:821A3:A4B2F:69F54A2D"},"id":"a14b6354-31fd-44b8-9408-71d6bda6c4be","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:49:58.135Z","parentId":"951b61f6-ed18-4e47-8edc-4e40312aed27"}
